class Solution {
    public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        if (n < 1) return false; // 0 and negative numbers are not powers of three
        double log = Math.log(n) / Math.log(3);
        return (log == (int) log); // check if the log is an integer
    }
}
```

In this solution, we first handle the edge cases where n is less than 1 and return false. Then we calculate the logarithm of n with base 3. If the result is an integer, then n is a power of three. The `(int) log == log` check is a common idiom in Java to check if a double is equal to an integer value. If the result is an integer, it will be equal to its casted value.

Note: This solution assumes the constraint `-231 <= n <= 231 - 1`, as the result of the logarithm will not exceed the range of an int in this case. If the range was larger, you'd need to consider a special case or use a library with extended precision arithmetic.

